  "prompt": "What does it mean if you have foamy urine?",
  "response": "Foamy urine can be a sign of several potential health conditions:\n\n1. Protein in urine (proteinuria):\n- Can indicate kidney problems\n- May be caused by diabetes, high blood pressure, or kidney disease\n- Excess protein causes urine to appear foamy\n\n2. Dehydration:\n- Can cause concentrated urine that appears foamier than usual\n- Drinking more water can help resolve this\n\n3. Urinary tract infection (UTI):\n- Can sometimes cause changes in urine appearance\n\n4. Kidney stones:\n- May cause changes in urine consistency\n\n5. Kidney disease:\n- Serious kidney issues can cause persistent foamy urine\n\n6. Diabetes:\n- High blood sugar can lead to protein in urine\n\n7. Pregnancy:\n- Can sometimes cause temporary foamy urine\n\n8. Certain medications:\n- Some medications might affect urine appearance\n\nWhile occasional foamy urine isn't always a cause for concern, persistent foaminess or accompanied by other symptoms like pain, changes in urination frequency, or blood in urine should prompt a medical consultation.\n\nA healthcare professional can perform tests to determine the underlying cause and recommend appropriate treatment.",
